**Two-candidate preferred:** ALP [+ alp_tcp +]% vs Coalition [+ coal_tcp +]%

**Majority required:** [+ hor_majority +] seats

**Senate (all 60 seats):**

ALP: [+ senate_alp_seats +] | Coalition: [+ senate_coal_seats +] | Other: [+ senate_other_seats +]

[? if alp_hor_majority : The ALP has won a majority in the House of Representatives. ?]
[? if coal_hor_majority : The Coalition has won a majority in the House of Representatives. ?]
[? if hung_parliament : Neither the ALP nor the Coalition has won a majority. A hung parliament may require negotiation with independents. ?]
[? if alp_senate_majority : The ALP has a Senate majority — legislation will flow easily. ?]
[? if not alp_senate_majority and alp_hor_majority : The ALP does not hold a Senate majority. Coalition senators may block legislation. ?]

@coalition_menu_australia
go-to: alp_majority_govt     if alp_hor_majority
go-to: coalition_majority_govt if coal_hor_majority and not alp_hor_majority
go-to: hung_parliament_menu   if hung_parliament

@alp_majority_govt
on-arrival: prime_minister = "Chifley"; prime_minister_party = "alp"; spd_in_government = 1; in_alp_majority = 1;
achievement: alp_majority_win

The ALP has won a majority in its own right. Ben Chifley continues as Prime Minister, with a strong mandate to pursue Labor's program: nationalisation of the banks, the welfare state, and full employment.

The Coalition opposition is in disarray. Menzies must rebuild the Liberal Party from opposition.

[? if alp_senate_majority : With a Senate majority as well, Labor can pass its full legislative agenda without obstruction. ?]
[? if not alp_senate_majority : The Senate, however, remains a battleground. The Coalition will use its Senate numbers to frustrate Labor's legislative program. ?]

- @post_election_government: Form the government.

@coalition_majority_govt
on-arrival: prime_minister = "Menzies"; prime_minister_party = "ll"; in_coalition_majority = 1;
go-to: coalition_takes_power

@coalition_takes_power

Robert Menzies and the Liberal-Country Coalition have won a majority. The long Labor government is over.

Menzies will be Prime Minister, with the Country Party's Arthur Fadden as his Deputy. Labor enters opposition under Chifley, though the Senate balance of power may soften the blow.

- @opposition_strategy: We must regroup in opposition.

@hung_parliament_menu
new-page: true

= A Hung Parliament

Neither the ALP ([+ alp_seats +] seats) nor the Coalition ([+ coal_seats +] seats) has a majority. [+ hor_majority +] seats are needed.

[+ other_seats +] independent[? if other_seats != 1 : s?] hold the balance of power. We must negotiate.

- @alp_minority_deal:    Seek ALP minority government with independent support.
- @coalition_minority_deal: Let the Coalition attempt a minority government.
- @new_election_hung:    Call a new election rather than negotiate.

@alp_minority_deal
view-if: alp_minority_possible
on-arrival: prime_minister = "Chifley"; prime_minister_party = "alp"; in_alp_minority = 1; party_resources -= 1;

Chifley approaches the independents. Most are rural conservatives who would normally support the Coalition, but several have personal disagreements with Menzies. A confidence-and-supply agreement is reached: the ALP will govern, the independents will support the budget but retain their freedom on other votes.

It is a fragile arrangement. Every vote will matter.

- @post_election_government: Form the government.

@coalition_minority_deal
view-if: coal_minority_possible
on-arrival: prime_minister = "Menzies"; prime_minister_party = "ll"; in_coalition_minority = 1;

Menzies strikes a deal with enough independents to form a minority government. Labor is in opposition.

- @opposition_strategy: We must regroup in opposition.

@new_election_hung
on-arrival: {!
    Q.next_election_month = Q.month + 3;
    Q.next_election_time  = Q.time  + 3;
    if (Q.next_election_month > 12) {
        Q.next_election_month -= 12;
        Q.next_election_year = Q.year + 1;
    } else {
        Q.next_election_year = Q.year;
    }
    Q.dissent += 0.05;
    Q.dissent_percent += 5;
    Q.party_resources = Math.max(0, Q.party_resources - 1);
!}

The Governor-General grants a dissolution. A new election is set for [+ next_election_month : month +] [+ next_election_year +].

The instability damages both parties, but the public mood is uncertain. Labor's internal factional tensions may surface during the campaign.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
@post_election_government

The new government is formed. Chifley's cabinet is sworn in.

Key portfolios:
• Prime Minister & Treasurer: Ben Chifley (ALP)
• External Affairs: H.V. Evatt (ALP)
• Immigration: Arthur Calwell (ALP)
• Labour: E.J. Holloway (ALP)

[? if alp_senate_majority : With both chambers, Labor can legislate freely. ?]
[? if not alp_senate_majority : The Senate will require careful management. ?]

- @main: Proceed to government.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
@opposition_strategy

Labor is in opposition. The party must decide its strategy:

- @opposition_militant:  Take a confrontational stance, opposing the Coalition at every turn.
- @opposition_moderate:  Offer constructive opposition, preserving Labor's credibility.
- @opposition_rebuild:   Focus on internal rebuilding and preparing for the next election.

@opposition_militant
on-arrival: left_fi_dissent -= 5; right_socdem_dissent += 8; industrial_dissent -= 3;

Labor will fight the Coalition tooth and nail. The unions will be mobilised, the Senate used as a blocking chamber where possible.

The risk: being seen as obstructionist by a public that may have tired of Labor after [+ n_elections +] election[? if n_elections != 1 : s?].

- @main: Proceed.

@opposition_moderate
on-arrival: center_dissent -= 5; left_fi_dissent += 8; right_union_dissent -= 3;

Labor will offer a responsible opposition — supporting good policy where it agrees, opposing what it must. This may help win back the middle-class voters who drifted to the Liberals.

- @main: Proceed.

@opposition_rebuild
on-arrival: dissent -= 0.03; dissent_percent -= 3; party_resources += 1;

The ALP turns inward: resolving factional disputes, rebuilding finances, and selecting policy positions for the next campaign. Chifley focuses on keeping the party together in difficult times.

- @main: Proceed.

*/

// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// SENATE BLOCKING LOGIC  (called from government affairs events)
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

function senateCanBlock(Q) {
    // Returns true if Coalition can block ALP legislation in the Senate
    return Q.senate_coal_seats >= Q.senate_majority;
}

function senatePassWithCrossbenchers(Q) {
    // Returns true if ALP can pass legislation with crossbencher support
    var alp_plus_other = Q.senate_alp_seats + Q.senate_other_seats;
    return alp_plus_other >= Q.senate_majority;
}

